replyContent: When you detach parts from the body of the aircraft they move as a group until they are reattached. You can work around this by having a second cockpit that you attach to disconnected a part group. You can then disconnect parts individually from the group even though it is not connected to the body of the aircraft. I hope that helps.

I'm very satisfied with how this game has turned out. I think that the 
countermeasures and the cruise missile were great additions to an already 
great game. I also like that parts can now take damage, and engines can 
catch fire. If I had one problem with the game, it would be the terrain. 
The mountains, and ice Island are quite unrealistic. This isn't a problem, 
and sometimes it's fun to swoop through the canyons narrowly avoiding the 
wall, but most times, the terrain is just unappealing. I would be happier 
with one very large island, and several smaller ones, with sequences of 
plains and mountains further inland, the higher mountains could have ice on 
them. This would give access to many other possible locations for airports, 
and other Interactive locations. Overall, I have no problems with the game, 
and I will continue to play it, but if I could change anything these would 
be some of the things. By far my favorite game, and I have enjoyed seeing 
it get better and better since 2015. Thanks guys!!

So far, I'm really enjoying this game. Getting used to building and controlling planes takes around 30 minutes (Depending on how fast you learn). But after that, building and controlling planes is really easy and enjoyable. The thing I really love about Simple Planes is that plane simulations are much more realistic than other plane-flying simulators. If your plane crashes, parts of your plane pop off realistically. Controlling a plane is pretty easy, depending on how you design the plane, and the graphics are pretty decent. The only thing I'm not a big fan of is that there is only one map that you can use to fly your plane in. Otherwise, it doesn't bother me that much, because I'm assuming the developers will add more to Simple Planes over time. Like I said, so far, I'm really enjoying Simple Planes, and your 5 dollars will be worth it if you're into planes and how they work. I hope this was helpful!  *Be sure to read Simple Plane's description for extra details.

I loved Simple Rockets so have been looking forward to this game and it doesn't disappoint.  Simply drag parts from the menu and click them together and you can quickly build your plane before taking it out for a spin.  Parts can also be edited to change wing size/shape, control surfaces etc. Another feature I'm glad they have added is the ability to mirror parts to the other side of the plane.  All in all - hours of fun! 10/10
